# Boot Token Cost & Compaction Problem

**Jiang | Director of Strategic Intelligence | Velorin System | March 29, 2026**
**Research commissioned by:** Christian Taylor (Chairman)

-----

## THE PROBLEM — DEFINED

On Sonnet 4.6 at 200K window, your session starts with a fixed overhead floor before you type anything:

|Source                                  |Typical cost|Avoidable            |
|----------------------------------------|------------|---------------------|
|System prompt (CC internals)            |~3-4k       |No                   |
|System tools (15 built-in CC tools)     |~12-16k     |No                   |
|MCP tool schemas (all connected servers)|20-98k+     |Yes — primary culprit|
|CLAUDE.md / memory files                |Variable    |Yes                  |
|**Boot floor total**                    |**~40-120k**|Partially            |

With 4 MCP servers that’s commonly 40-67k tokens consumed before message 1. At 200K window that’s 20-33% gone at boot — which matches the reported 22% observation exactly.

Compaction worsens it: Sonnet 4.6 at 200K auto-compacts at 83% capacity (~167K), reserving 33K for the process. Effective working window is ~147K minus boot overhead. With 40K boot cost you get ~107K usable — then compaction fires early and loses context fidelity.

-----

## ROOT CAUSES — RANKED BY IMPACT

### 1. MCP Server Tool Schemas Loading at Session Start (PRIMARY)

Every connected MCP server registers its full tool definitions — names, descriptions, JSON schemas, parameters — on every request, even when those tools are never used in the session.

Real documented costs:

- GitHub MCP (27 tools): ~18K tokens
- Filesystem MCP: ~13K tokens
- mcp-omnisearch (20 tools): ~14K tokens
- Playwright MCP (21 tools): ~13K tokens
- n8n-workflow-builder (10 tools): ~7K tokens

One developer documented 98.7K tokens (49.3% of 200K window) consumed by MCP tools before a single message. Another documented starting a session at 143K/200K (72%) with all servers active — 5.8% free space, before typing anything.

This is a confirmed architectural issue filed in multiple GitHub issues against claude-code (issues #3406, #7172, #11364, #13717). Tool Search (deferred loading) was introduced as the fix — but requires confirmation it’s active.

### 2. Running Sonnet 4.6 at 200K Instead of 1M

As of March 13, 2026, the 1M context window is GA at standard rates for Sonnet 4.6 — no price premium. But it requires “extra usage” to be enabled in account settings. Without it, you stay on 200K.

At 200K with 40K boot overhead: ~107K usable before compaction fires at the 83% threshold (~167K). Session depth: 15-20 productive turns before first compaction.

At 1M with same 40K boot overhead: ~790K usable before compaction threshold. Session depth: 100+ turns with zero compaction for most sessions.

Anthropic CPO confirmed a 15% decrease in compaction events since the 1M window shipped.

### 3. CLAUDE.md Loads on Every Single API Call

CLAUDE.md is not a boot-only cost. It reloads on every message for the entire session. A 500-line CLAUDE.md that costs 5K tokens costs those 5K tokens 50 times in a 50-turn session. Documented system prompt floor after compaction: consistently ~14,328 tokens — CLAUDE.md is baked into this.

Anthropic’s documented target: under 200 lines. Everything beyond that that applies to specific workflows (not every task) should be in Skills instead. Skills cost 30-50 tokens at boot and full content only when invoked.

### 4. Extended Thinking On By Default

Sonnet 4.6 with adaptive thinking defaults to “high effort” — it almost always activates reasoning. Thinking tokens are billed as output tokens. Default budget can be tens of thousands of tokens per request on complex tasks. For routine operational work (file reads, protocol execution, document management) this is unnecessary compute.

### 5. Compaction Itself Is Lossy

When compaction fires, 167K of rich context — exact error messages, file paths, code snippets, decisions — gets compressed into 11-19K tokens. The summary preserves rough intent but loses specifics. Each compaction event degrades session quality. Multiple compactions per session compound the degradation.

The real compaction overhead (excluding the always-present 14K system prompt) is 18-19K tokens of summary — but you lose 167K of context to get it.

### 6. Velorin-Specific: Boot Protocol as MCP Tool Calls

The Velorin boot sequence (reading Drive documents, GitHub files, agent configs) generates MCP tool calls. Each tool call result accumulates in context. The boot protocol is not just a one-time cost — the read content stays in context for the session. A boot that reads 20 documents via MCP generates 20 tool call results that all persist in the active context window.

